cicognara-rails.title: Add url for website on readme

comments.body:
Question:

Can we use the json we get from the getty resourcesync endpoint? Otherwise, if we're following see also from manifests we're not necessarily getting MARC. In the case used as a fixture for https://github.com/pulibrary/cicognara-rails/pull/354 it's pointing to a MODS/METS record.

Answer: no, doesn't look like this gives us the author, publisher, date type metadata

Fields we want to store / display:
https://github.com/pulibrary/cicognara-rails/blob/3d648ffd5142bf246ab6f63d33b9c384a5943d42/app/controllers/catalog_controller.rb#L109-L131

I've reviewed the notes from recent project calls, and there are definitely places where they assume the metadata from the Getty Research Portal is what we'll display. And looking at the seeAlso values, I do see some METS and other things there, not just MARC.

> Answer: no, doesn't look like this gives us the author, publisher, date type metadata

The items I looked at from the most recent dump (http://portal.getty.edu/resources/json_data/resourcedump_2019-10-14-part1.zip) had author/title/date/etc. info.

> I've reviewed the notes from recent project calls, and there are definitely places where they assume the metadata from the Getty Research Portal is what we'll display.

Awesome. Let's do that then. I guess the records will be somewhat variable. But presumably they can always enhance what they're sending to Getty.

Apparently the google oauth business requires a key. It didn't sound like we were really interested in messing with that for development purposes.

A workaround is to create a User in the rails console. `application_controller` then auto-logs you in during development. We should update the README to say this -- making this a documentation ticket.

comments.body: It's been a long time. Do we still need this feature?

I don't think this is a priority for this sprint — the project has decided to revise a set of MARC records (the first 1000) and work on resolving data quality problems with that subset. As part of that, we can determine if this issue needs to be addressed, or if the current data model is sufficient for the functionality we need.
Great. I'm gonna close this then.

figgy.title: Downloads fail for Google Drive batch ingests

comments.body: The authorization header is not being passed to the `PendingUpload`, and `FileAppender` download is not propagating the error in these cases.

https://figgy-staging.princeton.edu/catalog/bb7c062a-b580-4bad-98b8-7db84d72f1af verifies that the batch ingests are restored with https://github.com/pulibrary/figgy/compare/issues-3490-jrgriffiniii-google-drive-batch-ingest

figgy.title: Ensures that authorization headers are passed to the PendingUpload constructor for Google Drive resources
Default pulfa exporter to rails log so we can see it in datadog
Delete resources stuck in a bad "pending uploads" state

comments.body: I think we can find all these with `qs.custom_queries.find_by_property(property: "title", value: nil)`; haven't confirmed that retrieves the one in question, though. Also not sure if it will retrieve more than we're looking for. may need to further limit by created today.
Querying for nil with that query doesn't work unfortunately. It finds everything, weird side effect of the contains operator.
😆 no wonder it got hung up. I guess we should just look for resources with the pending uploads status. Maybe use read-only mode to ensure nothing is actually being ingested.

Resources which have `PendingUploads` as members have these removed with https://github.com/pulibrary/figgy/blob/master/app/services/file_appender.rb#L175. An error should be raised with https://github.com/pulibrary/figgy/blob/master/app/services/file_appender.rb#L68 in order to prevent this from occurring, but this is not occurring (hence, while HoneyBadger notifications do not report these failures).

I would propose that `PendingUploads` should not be removed if there are such failures, and such failures should be explicitly logged.
